One thing to note is that the data include years beyond 2021. These are projections based on modeling done by the gapminder organization. Start by importing the data.

From 1929-1934, Kazakhstan suffered from repeated occurrences of famine. Being unable to sustain the population at this time, gave way to low life expectancies, as well as a major drop in life expectancy between 1930-1935. The countrys involvement in World War 2 between the early to late 1940s may also be a contributing factor. After 1950, where we start to see consistent growth, Kazakhstan adopted the Virgin Lands Campaign, increasing its agricultural sector and allowing the support of a large demographic.
